            <head>
              <title type="main">
                <hi rend="i">BLAKE, THE SCULPTURE</hi>
              </title>
            </head>
            <p>The sculptor Nigel Ellis is showing his figure
                            “Blake” at St. James’ Church in
                            Piccadilly, where Blake was christened. The hope is to raise funds so
                            that the statue can be cast in bronze for a public
                            monument—perhaps in Bunhill Fields, where Blake is buried.
                            Ellis says, “I want the sculpture to embody in full, not just
                            portray, and be elevating and enjoyable with the exuberance of Blake
                            himself. Elsewhere, Ellis writes, “This is not strictly a
                            portrait of Blake, although it does refer to both his life mask, the
                            grimace of which it seeks to translate, and his wife
                            Catherine’s drawing of him as a youth.” The statue
                            took more than a year to complete. It was on show from 8 August to 15
                            September in Piccadilly. For further information contact St.
                            James’ Church, 197 Piccadilly, London W1V 9LF, or Nigel Ellis
                            at 44 Redchurch St., Shoreditch E2 7DP England. Photograph by Nigel
                            Ellis.</p>
          </div3>
